Rules for displaying data and using data:

Rule 1: If a city has never been searched before by an user, then the data needs to be scraped.
Rule 2: If a city has already been searched, it's dataframes must be stored locally for faster execution when comparing cost of living between capabilities or generating reports on the fly;
Rule 3: If a city has already been searched, data can only be updated if user manually updated the data by clicking "Refresh" button in report.html
Rule 4: If a city has been searched within 7 days from today - mark it with a tag: "Fresh Data"
Rule 5: If a city has been searched in between 7 and 30 days from today - mark it with a tag "Fresh Data" Last time updated mmm/dd/yyyy (example: jan/01/2026) - N days ago
Rule 6: If a city has been searched for more than 30 days - mark it with a yellow tag: "Caution" This data has more than 30 days and we suggest clicking Refresh button to be up to date with the latest prices
Rule 7: If a city has been searched for more than 90 days - mark it with a red tag: "Attention - last time updated more than 3 months ago. Please click Refresh button to update the data for this city"

